      <hr class="hr-dotted">
      <div class="anchor" id="uses"></div>
      <h2>Uses for washing soda</h2>
      <ul>
      <li><strong>Clean laundry</strong> and tough stains on fabric</li>
      <li>Clean stains on bathroom and kitchen surfaces</li>
      <li><a href="#stainless-steel">Remove stains and rust on stainless steel</a> (read more below!)</li>
      <li><strong>Scour</strong> cellulose fabric such as cotton canvas and linen to prepare for waxing and dying (i.e. remove grease and dirt accumulated in the factory)</li>
      <li>Soften hard water</li>
      <li>Food (do your own research!): Used to <a href="https://www.chinayummyfood.com/kansui-lye-water-alkaline-water/" target="_blank">make kansui (鹼水)</a> for making ramen, moon cakes, <a href="https://youtu.be/B8-4GHFjhDY" target="_blank">Chinese buns, and other wheat-based foods</a>; to give pretzels its dark brown colour</li>
      </ul>
      <hr class="hr-dotted">
      <div class="anchor" id="howto"></div>
      <h2>How to make washing soda</h2>

      <p><strong>Time needed:</strong> 10 to 30+ minutes depending on batch size</p>
      <ol>
      <li>
      <strong>Prepare a dry stainless steel cooking pot</strong>.</li>
      <li>Pour desired amount of <strong>baking soda into pot</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Turn heat on medium to high.</strong></li>
      <li>
      <strong>Stir regularly</strong> and break up any chunks.</li>
      <li>As the baking soda heats and water evaporates away, <strong>it will feel lighter and more airy to stir</strong>. <strong>Clumps present will start to disintegrate</strong>. You may see steam and air bubbles coming off of it. <strong>Careful not to breath in any powder</strong>.</li>
      <li>When there is <strong>no more clumps present, you have successfully make washing soda</strong>! <a href="#ph-test">Test it with a pH test strip to confirm</a> – it should have a pH of 11.</li>
      </ol>

